Subtraction is an operation that identifies the total count of objects in a collection of items after a specific count of items are removed from the starting total.

You can subtract two numbers by starting with an initial count, which represents the number to subtract from, and a second count which represents the number to subtract.  Then remove one from the starting count repeating this operation for the number of items in the subtract value.  

Subtraction is not associative, which means that the order in which subtraction is performed matters.  For instance, seven minus five (7 - 3) equals four (= 4) but four minus seven (4 - 7) equals minus three (= -3).

Fuel cells are devices that use a fuel and an electrolyte to turn a chemical reaction to electricity. They use the chemical energy in the fuel without using fossil fuels, fuel cells are used to generate electricity at the household, industrial, transportation and space applications. The combustion of the fuel, typically hydrogen, in a fuel cell produces electric current. The electrochemical reaction is oxidization and reduction of hydrogen, the fuel cell is not a body, and the electrolyte is not a thick membrane. If you're using a 3-wire plug, then the GFCI is not required.  As you note, a 60-amp GFCI is only  required for a 3-wire plug with an inlet at the outlet.  
As it turns out, all 3-wire outlets (R, R, G) are exempt from GFCI requirements, even when using a 60-amp GFCI.  (This is a matter of local code, since the same rule does not apply to 2-wire outlets.)  The GFCI requirement for a 60-amp GFCI is only needed when using a 3-wire plug.  I'm not sure of the technical reason for this, but it is the general rule.
Note that you can, of course, use a GFCI to protect a 3-wire outlet.  However, a GFCI will only protect the GFCI outlet.
As for your other question:  Is there any value to protecting the GFCI outlet with the GFCI?  The GFCI will still protect the outlet from somebody trying to put a wire in the GFCI outlet.  As long as the GFCI is capable of shutting down the GFCI outlet, there is no difference.

April 9, 2002

The widely publicized disappearance of two students in the Yucatan Peninsula has sparked a search for the missing.

The students, for whom the college is named, were last seen on the afternoon of March 8.

The students, 17-year-old Sonia Sosa and 15-year-old Cesar Vazquez, were walking along the beach near their homes in Tabasco State, when they were picked up by a state police helicopter.

"They were both wearing matching pink swim suits and shorts, and had plastic bags," said Delfin Rodriguez, deputy director of the Mérida State Police, the local police agency. "We think they were looking for the ocean."

Rodriguez said the students were taken to a hospital, where they were examined by doctors who found no trace of blood in their systems.

The students' disappearance has been linked to a similar case in Tabasco State two weeks earlier.

The two students had gone to a party in Mérida the night before, and got back to Tabasco State just before midnight. Police found the two students' parents on the highway about 30 miles from Tabasco, and they were found dead.

The state police have not said whether the two students were kidnapped or killed.

Rodriguez said the police are investigating whether the two students were killed by a group of people, but the Tabasco State police is investigating separately.

"We're not sure if it's the same group of people who killed the parents, or the group of people who killed the students," said Rodriguez. "We don't know who's after them."

The students' family is demanding answers from the state police, and has said that they cannot afford to hire the services of a private detective.

The college's president, David González, said he was told the students had gone to a party, but "all they knew was that they left."

"There was no evidence of their activities that night," said González. "We have no knowledge of the circumstances of the parents' death."

A search of the beach was being conducted, and the police were checking points along the highway where the students' parents died.

Ahonen, 28, was shot dead on Monday by a gunman who had entered the hospital with a male accomplice.

Ahonen’s colleague, Agron Hasolli, said on Wednesday the hospital had been in lockdown after the gunman was reported as having entered the building.

I worked at a United Kingdom large chain of supermarkets. We had a situation where one of our stores was selling a lot of very expensive goods (i.e. high-end items) that were in an unusual time-of-sale format (they were all either circular or next day sale). They were having trouble selling them because nobody wanted to buy them in the first place.
One of the stores had a formalised staff training program which was supposed to teach the staff how to ask and answer the right questions about the goods, what they were and what they were for. Yet this program was never actually implemented and the staff were simply given a series of training at the beginning of each store, with no actual work to do. So they were taught to ask the right questions with too little understanding of how the questions would be answered. It was a very sad situation, but the staff still did not know what they were doing and the manager did not know what the staff were doing. The store manager did not have any formal training, either, so he simply did not know what to do either.

A:

If your store are subject to the same time-of-sale transaction as a US store, then I think they will have an identical problem.
As such, the only work-around I can think of, is to hire a full-time salesperson for the time-of-sale transaction, and employ a full-time manager for the rest of the stores.
I do not think US stores would be willing to hire a full-time salesperson for such a role.  They would rather do it themselves.
Also, the head office in the US might be willing to do this for you.  It might also work if you are in a country where you are the only store.

There are many types of software pricing models, but broadly they can be divided into three categories: perpetual, subscription, and consumption.

Perpetual software pricing models, also known as perpetual licensing models, allow the software to be purchased for a one-time fee.  Typically the buyer has nearly unlimited use of the software in perpetuity.  If updates to the software are required, a separate software maintenance package may be purchased.

Subscription software allows unlimited use of the software for a predetermined period, often 1 year or 3 years, for a price.  Updates to the software are often included in the price of the subscription.  At the end of the subscription term, the buyer usually has the option to renew their subscription.

Consumption-based software allows the buyer to pay for their actual usage of the software during a period of time, for example monthly.  In this type of arrangement, the actual usage can vary from period to period, resulting in customer charges that vary as well.  Some customers like knowing that they will only pay for what they use, while other customers dislike the unpredictability of their bills.

Necrotizing enterocolitis (NEC) is a lethal gastrointestinal disease caused by bacterial translocation from the small intestine into the bloodstream. NEC has been reported in up to 15% of infants and is associated with high mortality rates. The incidence of NEC has been increasing, and the disease has been recognized to be a leading cause of neonatal morbidity and mortality in infants of >28 weeks' gestation. Although NEC is the most common gastrointestinal disease in infants, there are limited treatment or prevention options. A recent retrospective study reported that pathologic NEC was associated with high mortality, and the authors suggested that the development of targeted treatment strategies requires more data.

The mechanisms underlying NEC are not well-understood. In early studies, bacterial translocation was presumed to be the primary cause of NEC. However, the evidence for this theory has increasingly been challenged. The authors of the current study reported that, in a retrospective cohort of infants, NEC was associated with high rates of mortality. In addition, there was a stronger association between NEC and death than was previously described.

Interventions aimed at preventing NEC have met with limited success. In order to develop effective NEC prevention, the authors suggest that further studies of NEC pathogenesis and pathogenesis should be conducted. As such, a better understanding of the disease mechanism and the development of targeted treatment strategies will be needed.

2. It has been described as one of the best epic poems in Persian literature, comparable to Shahnameh, by Ferdowsi, and the most important work of Asadi Tusi.
3. Asadi Tusi completed the poem in 1066 and dedicated it to a certain Abu Dulaf, the ruler of Nakhjavan (nothing is known about him).
4. The poem has also been translated to other languages such as French and German. 
5. It seems that Asadi Tusi wrote this poem based on a written source.
6. Like the Shahnameh, it contains few Arabic loan-words and consists of some 9,000 verses.
7. The main hero of this epic poem is Garshasp, the son of Etret, and grandson of Sām.
8. The poem begins with the story of Jamshid and Zahhak.
9.  Jamshid is overthrown by Zahhak and flees to Zabol

Immediate Payment Service (IMPS) is an instant payment inter-bank electronic funds transfer system in India. IMPS offers an inter-bank electronic fund transfer service through mobile phones. The service is available 24x7 throughout the year including bank holidays. NEFT was also made available 24x7 from December 2019. RTGS was also made available 24x7 from 14th December 2020.

It is managed by the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) and is built upon the existing National Financial Switch network. In 2010, the NPCI initially carried out a pilot for the mobile payment system with 4 member banks (State Bank of India, Bank of India, Union Bank of India and ICICI Bank), and expanded it to include Yes Bank, Axis Bank and HDFC Bank later that year. IMPS was publicly launched on 22 November 2010. Currently, there are 53 commercial banks, 101 Rural/District/Urban and cooperative banks, and 24 PPIi signed up for the IMPS service.

The stock market helps companies raise money to fund operations by selling shares of stock, and it creates and sustains wealth for individual investors.

Companies raise money on the stock market by selling ownership stakes to investors. These equity stakes are known as shares of stock. By listing shares for sale on the stock exchanges that make up the stock market, companies get access to the capital they need to operate and expand their businesses without having to take on debt. In exchange for the privilege of selling stock to the public, companies are required to disclose information and give shareholders a say in how their businesses are run.

Investors benefit by exchanging their money for shares on the stock market. As companies put that money to work growing and expanding their businesses, investors reap the benefits as their shares of stock become more valuable over time, leading to capital gains. In addition, companies pay dividends to their shareholders as their profits grow.

The performances of individual stocks vary widely over time, but taken as a whole the stock market has historically rewarded investors with average annual returns of around 10%, making it one of the most reliable ways of growing your money.

Class C RVs are built on van or pickup chassis but the back is cutaway and a larger structure is added. Travel trailers are campers that are towed behind a truck or car and can range in size from very small to very large. Truck campers are carried in the bed of a pickup truck and provide a small, enclosed sleeping space.

Thursday, February 05, 2008

The Case for the Unnatural

Medical science is being challenged by "denialists" in the Christian community, who point to the existence of evil in the world and argue that God allows it. This is the subject of Ken Gire's post at Scepticism on the blog. The Christian deniers have a lot of evidence to back up their claim.

In the book Between God and Science, Paul Davies, a clergyman, scientist and the author of original research in the life of the cosmos, describes what he calls the "moral revolution" in science. It reached its zenith in the mid-1960s with the publication by eugenicist John B. Watson of the book The Miracle of Human Fertility.

label: Oxidation reduction potential or ORP is measurement for water.  A millivolt meter can measure ORP and it is a measure of the potential of water to carry or hold antioxidants.  It is not a guarantee of antioxidants in water.  One form of antioxidants in water is free floating dissolved hydrogen.  A good analogy of antioxidants in water is the following: ORP is like a big swimming pool of potential but at the moment its currently empty and dissolved hydrogen is like ball of finite size.  The larger the ORP'swimming pool' the more dissolved hydrogen 'balls' can fit in that pool.  An ORP with a large negative value is huge swimming pool, and an OPR with a high positive value is no swimming pool.  ORP can also measure whether water is acidic or alkaline.  ORP that is negative tends more toward alkaline water, and ORP which is positive tends more towards neutral water and acidic water.

Proposed following the often bitter 1787–88 debate over the ratification of the Constitution and written to address the objections raised by Anti-Federalists, the Bill of Rights amendments add to the Constitution specific guarantees of personal freedoms and rights, clear limitations on the government's power in judicial and other proceedings, and explicit declarations that all powers not specifically granted to the federal government by the Constitution are reserved to the states or the people. The concepts codified in these amendments are built upon those in earlier documents, especially the Virginia Declaration of Rights (1776), as well as the Northwest Ordinance (1787), the English Bill of Rights (1689), and the Magna Carta (1215).

How the new Channel 9 Spanish-language station in Denver, Colorado, began its life is now the stuff of legend. The station, which launched this month, is the brainchild of a father and son team whose combined education, experience, and financial prowess are a testament to the power of the technology revolution.

Rumors of the duo's involvement in the station began when a Denver television station announced that a local Spanish-language station would debut in early 2007. The station was to be the brainchild of television executive Bill Rabbitt -- the son of a former mayor of Denver -- and his father, Jeff Rabbitt. The elder Rabbitt had been a TV executive for many years and had worked for the cable television pioneer Ted Turner, who owned an independent station in Denver.

The name of the station, Channel 9, was actually drawn from the color of the channel on a television set. The station would broadcast in the Denver market at 720p, the same resolution as the local Denver-area channel. It would also broadcast in Spanish.

To some observers, Channel 9 was the logical extension of the success of the Denver affiliate of the Spanish-language network Telemundo, the Spanish-language channel owned by Univision. When that network debuted nine years ago, the Denver-based Telemundo station was the only market affiliate to broadcast in Spanish.

In fact, Telemundo had a hard time finding an affiliate in the Denver market. The national Telemundo network, which was launched in the 1980s, was the only major Spanish-language network to offer American programming. The network is broadcast in English in Spain and in Spanish in Mexico.

Channel 9 would be the first and only Spanish-language television station in the Denver market. The station would be based in Boulder, Colorado, and would launch with a program, a newscast, and a local newscast. The station would be anchored by a local news anchor, a reporter, and a studio host.

The location of Channel 9 was unique -- the station would broadcast from a unique structure on the campus of the University of Colorado at Boulder, on the 6th floor of the Center for Communication and Media Studies, at the University of Colorado.

Initially, the station was intended to be launched in the Denver market in early 2007, but it was delayed until October 2007.

And yet, as the saying goes, "Good presentation is not an art, it's a science".

There are no hard and fast rules for how to give a good presentation. Most of the time, the right way to go is to think of your presentation as a series of slides rather than one big presentation.

Following are a few of my favorite tips that have worked for me over the years.

1) Don't go overboard.

Don't try to do too much. Many people, myself included, tend to over-plan and over-design their presentations.

Instead, focus on what you can do rather than what you cannot. If you can't do everything, then pick your battles and focus on the things you can do. More often than not, that will be the things that you're most proud of.

2) Can't do that? Don't even try.

Prepare yourself for the unlikely case that you can't do something. Don't try and do it, just accept it and don't try to change it.

If you're trying to impress your audience, then you're more likely to think of your presentation as a series of slides rather than one big presentation.

During the strike the American Railway Union led by Eugene V. Debs boycotted the company following the panic of 1893 crippling railroad traffic in the United States. Porter wrote an essay titled "March Madness" in the Illinois Interscholastic in 1939 to commemorate the tournament. Other media outlets embraced the term as the tournament continued to sell out and thrive for decades. Brent Musburger, a former sportswriter from Chicago, brought the term "March Madness" to the NCAA tournament when covering the event for CBS in 1982. The phrase became synonymous with the tournament ever since. In 2010, the NCAA made it official and paid IHSA (The Illinois High School Association) $17.2M for the rights to the phrase, and began using the trademark in marketing materials, logos and other branding material. While only used for the men's tournament for decades, the NCAA only began using the phrase "March Madness" for the women's tournament in 2022.

input: How much music theory knowledge is required to compose music?
label:
Technically speaking, very little music theory knowledge is “required” to compose music. Music theory is, essentially, what musicians have learned over the course of several hundred years about how to write music that is interesting and sounds good. In other words, music theory is there to help you, not hold you back. 

When you learn music theory, what often happens is that you expand your broader understanding of music, which can be a very helpful safety net. The more music theory you know, the easier you’ll be able to distinguish between the good ideas and the not-so-good. You need to know the rules before you can break them. You need to be able to write by the book before you throw the book away. If not, you run the risk of writing music that’s not nearly as clever as you think it is, that tries to be daring and experimental but ends up just being dull and vanilla. And frankly, I just don’t see the value in ignoring all the work that centuries worth of musicians have done into knowing how music works. Putting the time into learning and really understanding it can only make you a better musician and a better composer.

Gravity is a fundamental interaction which causes mutual attraction between all things with mass or energy. Gravity is the weakest of the four fundamental interactions namely the strong, weak, electromagnetic and gravity. However, it is the most significant interaction between objects at the macroscopic scale, and it determines the motion of planets, stars, galaxies, and even light. 
Gravity is most accurately described by the general theory of relativity that was proposed by Albert Einstein. The theory describes gravity not as a force, but as the curvature of spacetime, caused by the uneven distribution of mass, and causing masses to move along geodesic lines.
However, for most applications, gravity is well approximated by Newton's law of universal gravitation, which describes gravity as a force causing any two bodies to be attracted toward each other, with magnitude proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.

As of some one gently rapping, rapping at my chamber door.
“’Tis some visitor,” I muttered, “tapping at my chamber door—
Only this and nothing more.”

Ah, distinctly I remember it was in the bleak December;
And each separate dying ember wrought its ghost upon the floor.
Eagerly I wished the morrow;—vainly I had sought to borrow
From my books surcease of sorrow—sorrow for the lost Lenore—
For the rare and radiant maiden whom the angels name Lenore—
Nameless here for evermore.

Tenor-saxophonists who want to play Tchaikovsky's The Nutcracker and the Four-Hour Opera for their employer should spend a few days with the National Symphony Orchestra in Washington, D.C. The orchestra plays the score in its entirety for an audience of about 2,000. (In the video above, the orchestra plays some of the music in a couple of different versions.)

The orchestra has been performing The Nutcracker for 40 years. While the performances are well-received, the legend behind the work is that it is "a big, big, big deal in the world of music."

The Nutcracker is an allegory of the Russian Revolution. In the ballet, the Nutcracker Prince's mother gives the Nutcracker Princess the Nutcracker to eat so her son can become a king. Instead, though, the Prince weds the Princess.

According to the National Symphony Orchestra's Web site, the Nutcracker is "the greatest musical representation of the Russian Revolution," and "is the first popular, operatic work to be written by a Russian composer."

"The Nutcracker is not about the Soviet Union," says John Mason, a violinist with the orchestra. "It's about the brotherhood of man, about love and respect."

If you're thinking of joining a concert band, orchestra or chorus, the National Symphony Orchestra is a good place to start. It has about 1,200 members. It's based in the District of Columbia, just a short drive from the nation's capital.

Let the number of ducks be X and the number of rabbits be Y.
We have X + Y = 25 and 2X + 4Y = 88.
Simplifying the first equation, we get Y = 25 - X
Substitute that in the second equation, we will get 2X + 4(25-X) = 88,
Thus 100 - 2X = 88
Which means 2X = 100 – 88 = 12, thus X = 6.
We substitute back into the first equation, we have Y = 25 - 6 = 19.
There are 6 ducks and 19 rabbits!

At small scales, physical matter exhibits properties of both particles and waves, and quantum computing leverages this behavior using specialized hardware. Classical physics cannot explain the operation of these quantum devices, and a scalable quantum computer could perform some calculations exponentially faster than any modern "classical" computer. In particular, a large-scale quantum computer could break widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations; however, the current state of the art is still largely experimental and impractical.

The basic unit of information in quantum computing is the qubit, similar to the bit in traditional digital electronics. Unlike a classical bit, a qubit can exist in a superposition of its two "basis" states, which loosely means that it is in both states simultaneously. When measuring a qubit, the result is a probabilistic output of a classical bit. If a quantum computer manipulates the qubit in a particular way, wave interference effects can amplify the desired measurement results. event.

abstract: 'We propose an inverse problem for a time-dependent diffusion equation driven by a non-autonomous, stochastic forcing. The problem is to determine the deterministic time evolution of the diffusion coefficient $\bf D$ of the solution to the equation. The problem is posed from the point of view of the time evolution of the solution to the equation. The solution of the inverse problem is given by an iterative scheme. We consider the problem with a random reflection coefficient $\rho(t)$, which is assumed to be a random variable whose distribution function $F(\rho)$ is given. We derive the solution of the inverse problem under the following assumptions on the random variable $\rho(t)$. The distribution function $F(\rho)$ is bounded away from zero and infinity. One of the assumptions is that the distribution function $F(\rho)$ is a strictly increasing function of $\rho$. The second assumption is that the distribution function $F(\rho)$ is a polynomial of degree at most one. We prove that if the random variable $\rho(t)$ satisfies the hypotheses then the solution to the problem is given by an iterative scheme. If the solution is given by an iterative scheme, then the iterative scheme is defined by an explicit formula. We denote this explicit formula by the formula $\bf{M}$ and we call it the formula of the iterative scheme. We discuss the properties of the iterative scheme and show that the iterative scheme is a consistent solution to the inverse problem. We show that the iterative scheme converges to the solution of the inverse problem if the solution of the inverse problem converges to a finite limit. We discuss the convergence of the iterative scheme and the convergence of the solution of the inverse problem. Our results are illustrated using numerical simulations.'

In Canada, the term automated banking machine (ABM) is also used, although ATM is also very commonly used in Canada, with many Canadian organizations using ATM over ABM. In British English, the terms cashpoint, cash machine and hole in the wall are most widely used. Other terms include any time money, cashline, tyme machine, cash dispenser, cash corner, bankomat, or bancomat. ATMs that are not operated by a financial institution are known as "white-label" ATMs.

If your gas water heater is not working, first check to see if:

 - Is the water heater leaking? If so, turn off the water and gas to the heater, and contact a plumber to replace the heater.
 - Do you smell gas around your heater? If so, you likely have a gas leak--turn off the gas line to the heater and contact a plumber to replace the heater.
 
If neither of these are issues, check to see if the pilot light for you heater is lit. This is likely hidden behind a panel or door on the bottom of the front of the heater.  If the pilot light is not lit, follow the instructions to try re-lighting it.

If the pilot light does not light or continues to go out after heating the water, the thermal coupling on the water heater likely needs to be replaced. Contact a plumber to have this replaced.

Generally speaking, traditional tank-based, gas water heaters have a lifetime of 10-15 years. If the age water heater is within this range, you may want to prepare for replacing the water heater soon.

Linux, computer operating system created in the early 1990s by Finnish software engineer Linus Torvalds and the Free Software Foundation (FSF).

In 1991 he released version 0.02; Version 1.0 of the Linux kernel, the core of the operating system, was released in 1994. About the same time, American software developer Richard Stallman and the FSF made efforts to create an open-source UNIX-like operating system called GNU. In contrast to Torvalds, Stallman and the FSF started by creating utilities for the operating system first. These utilities were then added to the Linux kernel to create a complete system called GNU/Linux, or, less precisely, just Linux.

input: What batting traits make a good baseball or softball hitter?
label:
There are many traits that great baseball and softball batters share.  Some of the most important are extreme confidence, sound batting mechanics, and coordination developed though a combination of talent and practice.  

All great hitters share some consistencies in their batting mechanics such as their lower half mechanics, their hand and bat path, and their head and eye movement.

With their lower half mechanics they generate powerful torque from the ground up by timing the planting their feet in a balanced position and forcefully rotating and opening their hips.  Hitting powerful line drives relies heavily on the barrel of the bat meeting the ball flush.  Batters increase the odds of this by keeping their hands in, connected to the back shoulder, and having one palm facing up and one palm facing down for as long as possible as the bat path travels through the strike zone.  Finally, all great hitters maintain consistent head and eye position throughout the motion. 

There are many nuances of batting mechanics that all great hitters share but these are some of the most important.

'Digital' Advertising Has a Political Problem

Digital advertising is more about the ad than the content.

But is it really?

The report warns that the 'digital' ad campaign is based on a false premise. It's about the same as a political campaign: the message is supposed to resonate--and there's evidence that it does, but the proof is in the pudding.

So what's the difference between the two?

With advertising, the message is what you've paid for. (The message, in the case of political ads, is what you're trying to convince someone to vote for you.)

With digital advertising, it's about the content, not the message.

The difference, says the report, is that the content of a digital ad and the content of a political ad are often the same.

The flip side of the same coin is that a digital ad has far fewer costs and more accountability than a political ad.

With digital advertising, you pay for the ad and the content.

With politics, you pay for the campaign and the ads.

So the report suggests that real-time digital advertising could be better for organizations than real-time political advertising.

But the report acknowledges that the technology is still in its infancy.

"The challenge is that digital advertising has a political problem," says the report's authors, Todd Bensman, director of research and development at the Manhattan Institute, and Jonathan Hsu, an assistant professor of marketing at the Stanford Graduate School of Business.

"The process of creating digital advertising is not an efficient one," says the report.

It notes that it takes months to produce a digital ad, and that the cost of producing it is not factored into the advertising campaign.

"There are a number of things that get in the way of the effectiveness of digital advertising," says the report.

And it says that there are many more challenges than just the technology.

"Organizations are paying a lot of money for digital advertising," says the report.

"One of the reasons they're paying so much money is so that they can reach as many people as possible. The process of creating a digital ad is not an efficient one. It's not a process that should be the responsibility of an organization."

WASHINGTON (AP) — The fake news media and Internet trolls are on a wild rampage against the White House and President Donald Trump.

Now, they are on their way to court.

The nation’s largest news organizations, including The New York Times, NBC and CNN, are suing the Trump administration for refusing to turn over an email exchange that they say was intended to damage the president.

The lawsuit was filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., seeking to force the Trump administration to produce the records.

Trump’s lawyer, Michael Cohen, said in a statement that the White House has merely been responding to requests from news organizations.

“The White House has received and responded to numerous document requests of various news organizations,” Cohen said. “Similarly, the White House has provided over 100,000 pages of documents to those news organizations for review and analysis, and has made multiple inquiries to news organizations for the same purpose. The White House has also provided tens of thousands of pages of documents to the Department of Justice, which has been reviewing them.”

The lawsuit alleges that the document exchange was intended to discredit the president and his family. But the president’s critics say that it was part of a wider effort by the president’s enemies to undermine him.

“These documents provide a window into President Trump’s organization, his campaign and transition team, his family, his administration, and the inner workings of his business,” the lawsuit states. “The documents are intended to damage President Trump and his family.”

Trump’s critics have spent years trying to discredit the president and his family. And though the president has repeatedly denied any collusion with Russia, they have seized on the emails as evidence that he colluded with Russia and hacked Democratic emails.

Trump has repeatedly denied the allegations, and the White House has said the president did not know that the Russians were trying to influence the election.

The president’s legal team has said the White House did not have adequate security to handle the sensitive information that was contained in the emails. On Wednesday, both Cohen and Trump’s personal attorney Rudy Giuliani said the president had not been told that the emails contained classified information.

The news organizations said they were seeking information on all of the emails from the Trump campaign, in the course of their investigation into Russian election interference.

“I don’t know how many times I’ve heard the phrase ‘I’m sorry to see this’ or ‘I’ve been waiting a long time for this,’” Djokovic said. “I think there were so many times when I was playing so poorly in the first two sets, and I was playing so much better in the third set. Murray was gracious in defeat.

Several have compared the Spaniard displaying his prowess on the red dirt to Picasso painting a live mural, Ennio Morricone producing a melody exactly congruent with the scenario, or Jorge Lorenzo posting similar times lap after lap in an almost mechanical yet fluid approach.

Rafael Nadal's ability on clay is mostly due to the surface itself. This may appear to be a quip, but the particular qualities of claycourts - which distinguish them from grass and hardcourts - are a fundamental reason why Rafael Nadal has dominated the surface the way he has.

What distinguishes clay? It's sluggish and bouncy. Fundamentally, clay reduces the speed of the ball once it bounces on the surface. Of course, there's more to it than just making the game slow and monotonous, but that's the distinguishing quality of a claycourt.

The surface is also less skiddish than grass or hard, allowing the ball to bounce high, which suits Rafael Nadal's high topspin-based game.

Here we report on the functional analysis of two ICBP90 mutants: the DBD-mutant (ICBP90-DBD) and a point mutation within the N-terminal region (ICBP90-Nter). WikiLeaks Reaches Enlarged Audience on Twitter: Report (Reuters) - WikiLeaks, the group of hackers who helped the U.S. government leak secret cables, has reached an audience of at least 100 million people on Twitter, according to a report Wednesday.

The news service Reuters quoted an unnamed source as saying the new audience is more than double the roughly 50 million followers the group had on Twitter in mid-March. LinkedIn and other online networks fell about 40 percent in membership compared to March, the source said.

The new audience is made up of people who have signed up for the social-networking website Twitter, according to the Reuters report.

Twitter had been skeptical about the group's credibility for some time, and its London-based security firm, Cloudflare, had complained that WikiLeaks was using its infrastructure to produce the leaks.

Earlier this week, Twitter said it would block users who were found to have subscribed to WikiLeaks, and it has also suspended the group's founder, Julian Assange. The social service said it is still considering how to regulate the group.

Twitter's decision to block the group came at a time of growing tension over the spread of sensitive information through social media networks. The U.S. Justice Department and a number of major tech companies have asked social-networking sites to help them identify who is behind dangerous websites and other extremist content.

But the Justice Department also said that social networks were helping to spread false stories about terrorism and other security threats.

WikiLeaks has been critical of the social networks, including Facebook and Twitter, that have been targeted by a number of the group's releases of hacked documents, and has pointed out that the services have been slow to tighten up their policies for dealing with the leaks.

Charges have been filed against Assange, who has been living in the embassy of Ecuador in London, and in May he was given a suspended prison sentence for jumping bail in Sweden.

WikiLeaks has been slow to respond to requests for comment from Reuters.

Forecasting with small datasets can be challenging, as many traditional methods require larger amounts of data for accurate predictions.
Here are few approaches that can help you.

Simple moving average: This involves taking the average of a certain number of past data points, and using it as the forecast for the next period. This method can be effective for stable time series with no trend or seasonality.

Exponential smoothing: This method assigns exponentially decreasing weights to past observations, with more recent observations being given more weight. This method can be effective for time series with trend and/or seasonality.

ARIMA: The AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) model is a popular choice for time series forecasting. It can be effective for small datasets if the underlying data follows a pattern that can be modeled using an ARIMA model.

Perez v. Campbell, 402 U.S. 637 (1971), was a case in which the Supreme Court of the United States held that Arizona's law suspending a driver's license was unconstitutional due to its conflict with the federal Bankruptcy Act under the Supremacy Clause of the Constitution.

The plaintiffs, Mr. Adolfo and Mrs. Emma Perez, were licensed uninsured motorists in the state of Arizona. Insurance was not required under Arizona law. Mr. Perez was involved in a traffic accident and, unable to pay the associated costs, soon filed for bankruptcy. Arizona, under its financial responsibility laws, withdrew the Perez' licenses, and the couple filed suit in district court, where their claim was denied. The Perez family's appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit was denied, and they subsequently appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which granted certiorari.

The four national languages of Switzerland are German, French, Italian, and Romansh. German, French, and Italian maintain equal status as official languages at the national level within the Federal Administration of the Swiss Confederation, while Romansh is used in dealings with people who speak it. Latin is occasionally used in some formal contexts, particularly to denote the country (Confederatio Helvetica).

In 2020, 62.3% of the population of Switzerland were native speakers of German (either Swiss German or Standard German) at home; 22.8% French (mostly Swiss French, but including some Franco-Provençal dialects); 8% Italian (mostly Swiss Italian, but including Lombard); and 0.5% Romansh.

The German region (Deutschschweiz) is roughly in the east, north, and centre; the French part (la Romandie) in the west; and the Italian area (Svizzera italiana) in the south. In contrast, continuous variables include infinitely uncountable values, for example, a variable over a non-empty range of real numbers. 

According to the number of objective functions, an optimisation problem is classified as single or multi-objective. input: Who are the main songwriters for the Grateful Dead?
output:
who are the main songwriters for the Grateful Dead?

The argument is both quite simple and very deep.

First, a bit of history. When recording for the Dead, engineers found it impossible to record the band live. So they created a studio version of the songs that they could work from. As the years went by, many of the songs were recorded in a studio in Hollywood, California, which would later become the home of countless classic movies.

This is how the Dead became known as the band that recorded many of the greatest songs of all time.

But what about the music?

The Dead’s music has been described many times as an extension of their music during the 1960’s. This has always seemed to me a bit odd. The Dead took the best of the Beatles and combined it with the best of the Stones, the best of jazz, the best of blues, the best of soul and the best of the early rock ‘n’ roll. They were obviously not going for a soft, “melodramatic” sound.

The Dead also experimented with different instruments. You could hear them using the guitar, piano, bass guitar and drums on many of the songs. This was in the time of the fuzz guitar and the fuzz bass. This is what we call “fusion” in music. In the Dead’s case, it was a combination of the best of Jazz, the best of rock, the best of blues and the best of soul.

It’s not the only time the band experimented with different instruments. In the early days of the band, they would play piano, organ, harpsichord, and even some djembes. The leader of the band, Jerry Garcia, was a well-known violinist. He would often play the violin to try to make it sound like a guitar. This, too, was part of the band’s experimentation.

The Dead’s music was also very different from the music that followed them. The Grateful Dead were very much in the “alternative” or “counterculture” thing. The first two albums of the Grateful Dead album series were a reaction to the Vietnam War. Along with other cultural changes, this was a time of great experimentalism in music. The Grateful Dead were the first rock band to use a harmonium as a lead instrument. This was something that the other rock band of the time had never
